{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660059"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22672"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22672"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is undergoing an emergency surgical procedure. On opening the abdominal cavity, this is what the surgeon sees (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3eyE0zwoRpXbKGcVfxtZ1IWiF6ZNe0.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would have been the most likely mode of presentation of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tender swelling in the groin","Colicky abdominal pain, distension and vomiting","Widespread and constant abdominal pain","Abdominal pain and absolute constipation","Upper abdominal pain and projectile vomiting"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe operative findings are those of distended loops of small bowel and a 30 - 40 cm long segment of ischaemic bowel. The most likely underlying cause would be adhesions within the abdominal cavity. One of these adhesions has developed into a band, which has trapped a section of small bowel. This has initially caused luminal obstruction of the intestine and as the obstruction has advanced, so the blood supply has been jeopardised. The patient\u0027s initial symptoms would have been \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolicky abdominal pain, distension and vomiting\u003C/strong\u003E. As ischaemia sets in, the pain would have become constant and there would have been clinical evidence of a localised peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmall bowel obstruction in adults most commonly arises from postoperative adhesions. Early presentation is usually with intermittent, cramping pain due to peristaltic waves against an obstruction, accompanied by abdominal distension and vomiting. As obstruction persists, fluid sequestration and bowel wall compromise can progress to ischaemia, with pain character becoming constant and signs of peritonism. Recognising this evolution helps distinguish simple obstruction from complicated obstruction requiring urgent operative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETender swelling in the groin\u003C/strong\u003E suggests an incarcerated or strangulated groin hernia causing obstruction. While a hernia is a recognised cause of small bowel obstruction, it is a less likely cause compared with intra-abdominal adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWidespread and constant abdominal pain\u003C/strong\u003E suggests established peritonitis or ischaemia at initial presentation rather than the typical early obstructive pattern. Whilst the operative finding of intestinal ischaemia would in this patient have changed the pain pattern, it would not have been the initial presenting symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal pain and absolute constipation\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of large bowel obstruction. In small bowel obstruction, patients often vomit early and may continue to pass flatus or small amounts of stool initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper abdominal pain and projectile vomiting\u003C/strong\u003E implies proximal gastric outlet obstruction or very high jejunal obstruction. Adhesive small bowel obstruction commonly presents with colicky central abdominal pain and abdominal distension rather than isolated upper abdominal pain with projectile vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adhesive small bowel obstruction typically presents with colicky abdominal pain, abdominal distension and vomiting.","Progression from obstruction to bowel ischaemia is suggested by evolving constant pain, peritonism and clinical deterioration.","Groin pain and swelling suggest incarcerated hernia, whereas early absolute constipation is more typical of large bowel obstruction."],"references":["Jackson PG, Raiji M. Evaluation and Management of Intestinal Obstruction. Am Fam Physiotherapy. 2011; 83:159-65."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22672"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22032"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22032"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3eyE0zwoRpXbKGcVfxtZ1IWiF6ZNe0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3eyE0zwoRpXbKGcVfxtZ1IWiF6ZNe0.jpg",